&gt; I cannot tell where you have your .class file since the javac 
portion of  your
&gt; build.xml is not shown.  I am assuming from the run-junit target 
that you have
&gt; created it in the same directory as the .java file?  If so, the 
problem is
&gt; Junit cannot find your class because it needs to have the basedir 
in it&#39;s
&gt; classpath and filenames must reference from the basedir so as to 
pick up the
&gt; package/directory name properly.
&gt; 
&gt; Based on the assumption that the .class file is sitting in 
${basedir}/test
&gt; beside the .java file, the following run-junit target works:
&gt; 
&gt;     &lt;target name=&quot;run-junit&quot; description=&quot;junit-run&quot; &gt;
&gt;         &lt;junit printsummary=&quot;true&quot; haltonfailure=&quot;false&quot;&gt;
&gt;             &lt;classpath&gt;
&gt;                 &lt;pathelement path=&quot;${basedir}&quot; /&gt;
&gt;             &lt;/classpath&gt;
&gt;             &lt;formatter type=&quot;brief&quot; usefile=&quot;true&quot;/&gt;
&gt;             &lt;batchtest fork=&quot;true&quot; todir=&quot;${test}&quot;&gt;
&gt;                 &lt;fileset dir=&quot;${basedir}&quot;
&gt;                          includes=&quot;**/*Test.class&quot;/&gt;
&gt;             &lt;/batchtest&gt;
&gt;         &lt;/junit&gt;
&gt;     &lt;/target&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; You might want to consider implementing a directory structure 
along the lines
&gt; of:
&gt; 
&gt; basedir
&gt;     src
&gt;     testsrc
&gt;     build
&gt;         classes
&gt;         lib
&gt;     lib
&gt; 
&gt; to keep the .class files away from the .java files for ease of 
cleaning up,
&gt; building jars, etc...
&gt; 
&gt; Regards,
&gt; 
&gt; Lynne
